  "prompt": "Is the activity of money laundering prohibited?",
  "response": "Yes, the activity of **money laundering** is strictly prohibited and illegal in almost all jurisdictions worldwide. Money laundering involves disguising the origins of illegally obtained funds to make them appear legitimate. It is a serious criminal offense because it enables criminal activities such as drug trafficking, terrorism, fraud, and corruption to thrive.\n\n### Key Points:\n1. **Legal Framework**: Most countries have laws and regulations that explicitly criminalize money laundering. For example:\n   - In the **United States**, the **Bank Secrecy Act (BSA)** and the **USA PATRIOT Act** establish strict anti-money laundering (AML) requirements.\n   - The **European Union** has directives like the **Fourth Anti-Money Laundering Directive (AMLD4)** to combat money laundering.\n   - International bodies like the **Financial Action Task Force (FATF)** provide global standards to combat money laundering and terrorism financing.\n\n2. **Penalties**: Individuals and organizations involved in money laundering can face severe consequences, including:\n   - **Fines**\n   - **Imprisonment**\n   - **Asset seizure**\n\n3. **Obligations for Businesses**: Financial institutions (e.g., banks, credit unions) and other regulated entities are required to implement AML programs, report suspicious activities, and conduct customer due diligence to prevent money laundering.\n\nIn summary, money laundering is universally prohibited because it undermines the integrity of financial systems and facilitates criminal activities.",
